+# ADR-0002 · Architecture overview of the ai-paralegal codebase
+
+- **Status:** Accepted (descriptive — orientation record, no code change)
+- **Date:** 2026-05-26
+- **Driver:** Idea — "Give a one-paragraph architecture overview of THIS codebase: stack, main modules, entry points."
+- **Author:** Solution Architect (automated review)
+- **Builds on:** [ADR-0001](./ADR-0001-credential-access-audit-log.md) (structured-event-log / tenant-context patterns referenced below)
+
+## Context
+
+A concise, evidence-grounded architecture overview was requested. This ADR records it so future
+analyses build on a shared map rather than re-deriving it. Inspected: `package.json`, `README.md`,
+`src/app/*`, `src/features/*`, `src/lib/*`, and `docs/adr/ADR-0001`.
+
+## Decision (the overview)
+
+**ai-paralegal ("Wexford & Lane") is a Next.js 16 App-Router + React 19 + TypeScript-strict +
+Tailwind v4 application** — a design-and-architecture scaffold for an AI virtual paralegal for
+solo/small personal-injury firms, with data and integrations mocked. **Entry points** are the
+App-Router routes under `src/app/`: the root layout (`src/app/layout.tsx`), marketing (`/`,
+`page.tsx`), brand landing (`/landing-claude`), the product dashboard (`/dashboard`), and matter
+views (`/matters`, `/matters/[id]`). **The work is organized as feature modules** under
+`src/features/` — `ops-board`, `matters`, `medical-records`, `demand-letter`, `discovery`,
+`settlement`, `sign-off` — each exposing a barrel `index.ts`, a `"use server"` `actions.ts`
+mutation surface, in-memory `store.ts` mocks, `types.ts`, and (where AI is involved) a `prompt.ts`.
+**Two architectural choke-points govern the system:** (1) every model call routes through the single
+Gemini call site `src/lib/ai/callAI.ts` (ESLint blocks `@google/generative-ai` imports elsewhere),
+which also handles multimodal OCR inline; and (2) every outbound legal text must pass
+`verifyCitations()` in `src/lib/citations/verify.ts` — the only producer of branded
+`VerifiedDocument` — enforcing the "0 hallucinated cites" promise (CourtListener REST v3, with a
+local heuristic fallback). **Cross-cutting concerns live in `src/lib/`:** branded multi-tenant
+isolation (`tenant.ts` — `TenantContext` threaded through every call), a closed-union structured
+logger (`logging/`, the only sanctioned log path), a `Result` type for typed errors, a storage
+abstraction (`storage/`), and UI primitives in `src/components/ui/`. Conventions are codified in
+`docs/CULTURE.md`; production target is Google Cloud Run + Firestore + CMEK Cloud Storage + BigQuery.
+
+## Consequences
+
+- **Positive:** Clear feature-module boundaries + two enforced choke-points (AI, citations) make
+  cross-module impact predictable. Branded tenant/citation types push safety into the compiler.
+- **Documentation drift (verified):** `README.md` states "Next.js 14" and "Three routes", but
+  `package.json` pins `next ^16.2.6` / `react ^19.2.6` and `src/app/` has **5** route groups
+  (matters routes are undocumented). The README project tree omits `demand-letter`, `discovery`,
+  `medical-records`, `settlement`, `sign-off`, and `lib/citations|ai|logging|storage|tenant`.
+- **UNVERIFIED:** Runtime behavior not executed; assertions are from static inspection only.
+
+## Task breakdown — doc/architecture hygiene (total 5 pts)
+
+1. **Sync README stack to reality** — change "Next.js 14" → 16, note React 19. *(1 pt)*
+2. **Document the matters routes** — add `/matters`, `/matters/[id]` to the README route table. *(1 pt)*
+3. **Update README project-structure tree** — list all 7 feature modules + the `src/lib/*`
+   sub-packages (ai, citations, logging, storage, tenant, result). *(2 pts)*
+4. **Cross-link CULTURE.md sections** — README "Design system"/structure should reference the
+   CULTURE.md §-numbers the code comments already cite. *(1 pt)*
+

